Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @cauliflower florets{10%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Halve, peel,
and finely dice half the @yellow onion{1} (whole onion for 4 servings). Drain
@chickpeas{13.4%ounce}, reserving ¼ cup liquid (½ cup for 4). Pick
@cilantro{¼%ounce} leaves from stems.

In a #medium bowl{}, toss cauliflower with a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp},
@curry powder{1%tbsp}, and a couple big pinches of @salt{pinch} until coated.

Spread cauliflower out on a #baking sheet{}; roast on top rack until tender,
~{20-25%minutes}.

In a #small pot{}, combine @jasmine rice{½%cup}, ¾ cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4
servings), and a pinch of salt. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to
low. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat.
Add onion and a pinch of salt and @pepper{}; cook, stirring occasionally, until
lightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add chickpeas and half the @garam masala{1%tsp} (all for 4 servings); cook,
stirring occasionally, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @curry sauce base{5%oz}, reserved chickpea liquid, @sugar{½%tsp} (1 tsp
for 4 servings), ¼ cup water (½ cup for 4) to pan with chickpeas. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove from heat; stir in @butter{2%tbsp} (4 TBSP for 4) until melted. Taste and
season with salt and pepper.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; divide between one side of each bowl. Serve chickpeas
next to rice. Arrange cauliflower in the middle. Drizzle with
@yogurt{2%tbsp}. Sprinkle with cilantro leaves and serve.